< Review>
Been going to this club for over four years and had only a positive experience.  One main thing that stands out is that there seems to be low employee turn over, most of the faces are the same as when I started.  I did get a glimpse into one reason this may be, when one day I overheard, Marie, telling another employee that she does a great job and they are happy with her work.  Also, I never get bored as there's a wide variety of ways to work out.  The gym is clean and equipment seems to get fixed in a reasonable time frame.  Dues are a little on the high side, especially for new members, but the up side is that the money appears to be going back into the club in the way of maintenance and new equipment.  üèä‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏èüèãÔ∏è‚õπÔ∏è‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è<//Review>

< text>
The aqua pool was very cold last week and on and off the week before. The pool's temperature is not monitored carefully to detect when the heater is beginning to malfunction. The pool is suppose to be at 86 degrees; this is important for people with arthritis and disabilities that can only get their exercise in this pool.

The manager told me there are "engineers" that are in some sort of charge of the pools during the day and it is assumed that the pool temperature is checked daily, but there is no record kept of it. They mainly depend on customers complaining that the pool is too cold. The pool is not monitored for temperature at night when the pool is closed. If the heater has broken down at night no one knows about it until a customer steps in it in the morning. The workers at the desk do not know the temp of the pool, they only know if customers complain. A few can still swim in it if it is a little cooler; it would be good if the temperature was known. Some proactive monitoring of the temperatures would detect when they begin to drop so a malfunction can be found immediately.

Do they need a fundraiser to help them get an iPhone App that monitors the temp in the pool? Because the 2 million dollar addition they are putting in perhaps has drained the budget?</text>

< rating>
5<//rating>
<Review>I have a a family pass for four (2 adults and 2 children) and have enjoyed all of the amenities that this gym has to offer!  We did pay 1 year in advance to get a cheaper rate and not have the headache of monthly fees which has been great. I initially joined the gym for the lap pool but have been using the indoor equipment as well for cardio and strength workouts.  I have been a member at various gyms outside of Chico including Sacramento and Bay Area and this is the first with practically everything (including day care!).  Some reviews on here seem to forget how fortunate we are to have a facility like this in this area... Yes, I have come to the gym when the lap pool was closed or the sauna (hot room) wasn't working or some of the equipment was in repair, but come one, these guys operate almost 24/7 with constant use, I don't think its a huge inconvenience when some of these areas need to be repaired once in awhile - in those cases I just adjust my workout and move on. I come to the gym 2 - 4 times a week during the "off hours" like 7 pm -8 pm or 12 noon so I never battle crowds but understand it can get very busy; as someone mentioned before, you might just have to adjust your workout plan or times but this is the same issue at most gyms. If in motion capped their membership I think there would be many more upset customers than happy ones at this point especially because In Motion still has plenty of workout space. If you're a parent, the day care is a life saver...it does get busy sometimes but I have never had an issue with my kids going there. I wish the hours were a bit longer on the weekdays and earlier on the weekends but by no means a deal breaker. Some equipment could use a facelift as some weight plates stick sometimes or equipment is a little outdated but you can almost always find what you need for what it is you're working out. The classes are also a great feature (my wife goes to a few). Btw.. the rates are pretty fair considering all of these amenities.. On the conservative side its about $100 per month for family which is $25 per person per month..this includes day care, classes and a full locker room with steam room and sauna as well as all of the pools. I used to pay $30 per month just for my self at a local gym with small space and only weight machines. All in all it has been great! I haven't had to complain yet and my interaction with management has been minimal  but staff seem happy and are always nice.<//Review>< pictures>
None< /pictures>

<rating>4<//rating><review>I find smaller facilities are more personable.  It's not that the staff are unpleasant, but sometimes the right hand doesn't know what the left is doing--i.e.15 minute wait for towels to get out of the dryer.  I was disappointed in lap pool access--led to believe that most lanes are available for lap swim, but, in reality, the majority of the lanes are in use by swim groups and swim clubs during the prime swimming periods--i.e. when the sun is not full bore.  There are supposed to be three lanes open at all times for members, and members are good about sharing these lanes. But,with such a large membership(and with provisional reservation of 1/2 of the last lane for lessons), the lanes become overcrowded and problematic.  The club will say that 79% of the swimming hours are open to members, but I would contend that those hours are during high sun and on weekends.  Still, I give it a four star overall.< /review>< Pictures>

<user>115570913187899037746</user><Name>Rick Johnson<//Name><time>1404674434630< /time><rating>1</rating>< Review>
I pay a premium so that my family can have a membership here. The gym itself is fine (nothing amazing) but the service and the way they treat members is appalling. You want to swim in the lap pool? You'd better be at least 14 years old -- and KEEP MOVING AT ALL TIMES!!! (Apparently, sometime in the distant past, a group of 13 year olds caused problems in the lap pool; so, obviously the only solution is to punish ALL under-14-year-olds and their families, even though you pay the same price no matter the age.) They do have a "resort pool" (shaped like a kidney bean and about the same size), but you have to be willing to put up with kids bouncing off of you. (You do get the added bonus of the special additive they put in the water, which comes out of the bladders of all the kids who splash around there... I wonder if they charge extra for that?) They also have another pool, perfect for families; oh, that one is reserved for swimming lessons, even in the off-season when there aren't any lessons given, so tough luck. Did you forget your card to check in? Well, that's too bad; no matter the fact you PAY OUT THE NOSE to have the honor of using the gym AND THEY HAVE YOUR PICTURE ON FILE, they will no longer let you in. That's right, their valued customers will get turned away at the door. (Again, in the recent past they used to let you just sign in, but again apparently some people abused this courtesy; so, of course the solution is to treat all of their paying customers who forget their cards like dirt.) And the counter people look at you when you walk in like they're doing you a favor, and you're inconveniencing them by making them pause in the middle of their personal conversations. It is amazing the way they treat families here (and most certainly not in a good way.) I don't know if their staff just isn't trained to give good customer service, or if they ARE actually trained to look at their gym members like they're lesser people (although the fact that their policies are very anti-member makes me suspect the latter). I know the solution would be to change gyms, but this gym is right down the street, and that convenience is the only thing that actually gets my lazy butt to the gym. So, I just take it with a smile, and complain about it later.< /Review>

<user_id>108870089475376840863</user_id><name>David Gong<//name><date>1512844697182<//date>< Rate>
2< /Rate>
< review>
Hired this company to replace my water heater and also to install a pressure regulator to my water main. While there were some positives to the experience, overall, I feel like an honest, non-compensated review would be helpful to others who are considering these guys.

First, I'll list the positives. While On Call wasn't the cheapest, they also were far from the most expensive. I ended up with a water heater that (I believe) is a good one. And while there were several issues throughout the process, I believe Natalia is a well-intentioned person.

Now, onto the issues/concerns. First, and I chalk this up to my inexperience, is that they don't take care of securing a city permit before doing the work. Given that I had other projects involving city permits where the contractors handled that, I was surprised to find out, after the fact, that they didn't do this. To be honest, I don't know if that's standard practice with other water heater folks, but I think it's good practice to at least state upfront to customers whether they plan to secure a permit.

If they had secured a permit, then I'm sure they would've installed the water heater properly. As it is, though, what I ended up getting was an installation that would not pass an inspection. They did not bother putting the cover back onto the water heater, which is illegal. They left the relief valve exposed, which is against code. And simple things such as positioning the water heater properly was overlooked. It will cost me a ton of money to resolve the issues from the shoddy installation, which makes me realize I should've just hired someone else to do it right from the get-go.

Another issue is that constant need on my part to follow up to get a timely/accurate response to things. From making sure they showed up to the appointment on-time to getting paperwork for the extended warranty to getting answers to simple questions, I just had to spend way too much time to get follow-through on things that should've been done automatically.

Another biggest issue, however, was the result of their putting the pressure regulator on my water main. The problem stemmed from their on-site estimator making a wrong assumption on pipe fitting, which then led to the actual installer having to jerry-rig some makeshift solution on the spot. It's hard to describe in words, but the end result was a ridiculous looking configuration that rendered a key feature of my front porch unusable, since the height of the pipes went from a few inches off the ground to about a foot high. To Natalia's credit, she did try to get the installer to remedy this, but at that point, they already felt like they undercharged me so I don't think they tried their hardest to do the job properly. I ended up having to hire another plumber and paying hundreds of dollars to fix their handiwork.

The above is reflective of my caution with this company for others. Again, I felt like they had some level of genuine interest in addressing the poor workmanship, but there really shouldn't have been poor workmanship to begin with.

Also, I don't love that some of the reviews for this company were submitted by employees and their family members. And the company offers a $10 off per review incentive to customers, which is tempting as a customer, but ultimately not very ethical as a business.</review>

The place is bright, colorful and inviting. Lots of tables and nice place to enjoy your cupcakes.
First problem was that the menu was on a piece of laminated paper at the order window. So you had to be in the spot to place your order before you can see the menu. ?? No wonder it takes so long to get through the line. So you choose while feeling the pressure of the line of people behind you. They have a nice variety of cupcakes but like I said you have to choose in a rush. Also, we wanted ice cream. So again a rush to order because others were waiting. We chose coffee ice cream in a cup and captain crunch in a waffle cone. The ice cream was not so good. Very bland flavors and it melted sooo fast! I hate ice cream that melts fast!
The cupcakes were quite good. We got Red Velvet, Black and White and Cuban Coffee.
Great cupcakes, colorful and fun atmosphere but I wouldn't recommend the ice cream. It's called Sprinkles Cupcakes, not Sprinkles Ice Cream.</Text><Resp>None</Resp><rating>3</rating></record>

<text>A small cupcake store located inside the Americana in Glendale.  It's located right by the Cheesecake Factory and elevators of the parking garage.  They have a wide variety of flavors including seasonal and holidays varieties.  They also have a 24 hour cupcake ATM on the side of the building just in case you wish to get one after their normal operating hours.  However the selection of the ATMs are limited so keep that in mind.  I tried a few of their flavors of their cupcakes and ice cream and they were all pretty good.  A good place to stop by after a day of shopping for a treat.</text><pictures>None<//pictures>< response>

The location is great, employees are nice. They have 2 gluten-free options. (GF chocolate chip cookie or GF red velvet cupcake.) The ATM is a novel concept.

The icing is far too sweet; the cake part of the cupcakes were good and most. They were light and fluffy. Cupcakes are about $3.50 each. They also serve ice cream and a few assorted bottled (non alcoholic) beverages.</Review>

< review>
Greedy and rude

As one of the few fortunate enough to not be financially impacted by the pandemic, I try to funnel any of my purchases through our local businesses to help support the community. I know that it will cost me slightly more than I could easily find online or outside of Bakersfield, and I can live with that, especially in times like these. However, this store has been a rip-off before the pandemic and continues to be so during.

As an authorized dealer of particular brands, they get substantial discounts on products and funnel none of those savings to their customers. Instead, they charge more than what you can purchase the item from the manufacturer directly. When working with authorized dealers other than this store, I can easily get ~22% discount from MSRP on this brand. I was not expecting Roger's to do this, but I know I can get this deal. The item I was looking to purchase was a few hundred, not few thousand, so I was willing to pay MSRP but was hoping for below. However, this store offered me a price higher than MSRP even after I had already told them I called the manufacturer before coming in, so I know what I would pay if ordering directly. I responded by thanking them for their time, but I would be purchasing direct. Before I could even finish my sentence, the sales representative had already turned around and walked off. The store was empty, so there was no other person that they needed to rush to assist.

This was my second attempt at trying to offer my business to them. Last year when interested in an item of much higher value, I asked Roger's to match a deal another Authorized dealer has presented to keep my business local. They weren't willing to do so. So, I bought the item at the discounted 22% mentioned earlier from another store and went on my way.

Anyone shopping here is clearly getting ripped off.</review>

I went to Rogers looking for help. I know a little but I can't claim to be GIA Certified. A Hispanic lady whose name I cannot recall asked if I needed help and I gave her my ring, an emerald on 18k gold, and she advised me that her manager was GIA Certified. They took a close look at the ring and told me it was NOT an emerald ring and it was in fact a Jade. I trusted them and left. I was very disappointed in what I had purchased, it came all the way from Israel, and I wanted an official appraisal so I could return what I thought I had purchased was a genuine emerald. < text>
I  bought my husband's wedding band from Rogers. We instantly clicked with our salesman, Eason. He was also engaged and getting married soon. He was such a great help picking the perfect band for David. He patiently showed us all the rings we wanted to see. Very knowledgeable, explaining all the pros and cons of all the different metals and answering all our questions. My wedding band and engagement ring were purchased previously elsewhere, but we decided to keep going to Rogers because of Eason to have my set soldered together. We've had Rogers repair my ring twice since, for a broken prong and and again for new setting due to bent prongs on the main center diamond.  I'm apparently pretty hard on my jewelry! Also had to have my set resized smaller, they took care of that too with a pretty quick turnarourd every time. Eason even comes by my work on his lunch breaks to take my ring in to have it cleaned for me because he knows I don't always have time to drop it off myself. That is true customer service, above and beyond. I highly recommend Roger's. If you're thinking of buying jewelry, always ask for Eason! He's amazing! We will never buy jewelry anywhere else now because of him! Customers for life!< /text>

< text>
Flutter is a interactive exhibit in which you can submerge yourself. I only gave it 4 stars, because I wish the exhibit had been larger. There are mirrored rooms with mylar, furry rooms you can touch, and rooms you can sit and chill out. My favorite room has projectors and plays music to videos of oceans, trees and other calming images. Overall, it was a place to turn off your brain.</text>
</record></dataset><record>

Wonderful! Spent a joyous Sunday morning playing and laughing with my husband in each of the nine rooms. From sitting quietly coloring printed pages to sitting in a bathtub full of rubber ducks to dancing around in a mirrored room, we had a fabulous time. Our favorite was the room lined with reflective silver mylar balloons listening to a gentle stream while a  giant eyeball watched us from a screen. Sounds weird but it was actually very peaceful and relaxing! Thank you so much for putting together this wonderful playhouse and can't wait to be back in a few months for a whole new experience! Go early so you can take your time and bring your cameras!< /Text>

<Date>1573200578936<//Date><Rating>5</Rating>< Review>
I came here with my friend from the Bay Area. He's been to pop-ups in SF before, so he wanted to find one for us to do while he was visiting LA. He found Flutter for us, and let me tell you. We walked in and the owner told us it was a space that was so much more, and he was right!

I would recommend spending a little bit of time taking in each room, I feel you might find something a little deeper than an instagram-able post (however, it is also that! and you can get creative with it).

Would definitely recommend coming here with an older demographic that can appreciate it for art, and not just because it's interactive.

It's a permanent space, but the installations will change, so catch them while you can before they change them in a few months!

PS. there are no shoes allowed, so if you want to take good pics, incorporate some cute/nice socks as part of the fit!!</Review>

<name>Bella Clemons Duarte<//name><userid>115862574330058739347</userid><Response>None</Response><gmap_id>0x80c2b9d0fe6cf4a1:0x4ca38bc4c9043d0c< /gmap_id><Time>1577561683947</Time><Review>Very fun place ! Lots of cool exhibits</Review><Pictures>None<//Pictures><Rating>5</Rating></record>

<user_id>101466442122096967700</user_id><Name>Percival Gonzaga< /Name>< time>
1569571346695< /time>
< rate>
5<//rate>
< review>
This is a fun interactive museum that features a combination of projections and motion tracking. Most of their exhibits can be touched, and some, even altered.

My favorite room is the one in the far back that has the wide screen projection image with the 4 pillars of lamps illuminating the raised stage. That one my friend and i played with a lot. It takes a little bit for the images in the background to cycle, so if you missed a particular visual, you dont have to wait that long for it to reset. The music in that room is pretty calming, too so you can relax while you wait.

In your visit, be prepared to come in with socks or shoe covers. This is how they are able to keep their show floor clean and without any marks or smudges. Unfortunately, being bare foot isnt an option, but for the most part, it didnt hinder our experience. They have a shoe rack on the side to leave your shoes at.

Also, if you plan to take pictures at the entrace or some video, it looks like a light hallway, so i best suggest coming in later in the night so you get the full spectrum of colors from what looks like a runway through the glass display.

Overall, my model and i had a great time. There was a lot of street parking, and because we came in a little later in the day, the meters were already expired or offline, but during the weekends its not so busy, and youre able to pretty much have the room to yourself. Just be mindful about the other visitors if youre in the same room for an extended amount of time.</review>

None</Resp>

109155482002053692791</userid>
<user_name>Blake Wachob</user_name>< Date>
1607298688783< /Date>
<rating>5<//rating>< review>
Ordered for pickup 12/6/2020

The food is excellent!

The meat is heavily seasoned and the pico is spicy. Chicken tinga border burrito was massive and flavorful. I got plenty of sides. My only complaint is their flan isn't always available because it's actually home made.

Also they have been super solid at adapting to covid. During the beginning of the crisis they rolled out adds saying "we deliver" and it was some of the best food I had during lockdown.

The dollar tacos are fire. You have to pay 3.50 for a drink to get the dollar tacos so heads up. I don't mind at all they are worth it! I got 10 carnitas tacos and they came with plenty of lime.

I grew up on the Arizona border. This food reminds me of home and the staff were on point. Also I dunno if this is true but these corn tortillas on my tacos taste home made.

10/10 perfect and a lot better than other options in town.</review>

<user_id>111111232027161880950< /user_id><user_name>Michael Anderson</user_name><Time>1525176970626< /Time>< rate>
3<//rate>
<Text>My family had an odd experience recently.

My Dad, Mom, Partner and our 4 year old Son come here about once a month as it is close to my parents house and we generally agree on mexican food.

Normally the experience is 4+ star review quality, but nothing really to review on. As the food is worth what you pay for and I don't leave wanting or dissatisfied. But it's also usually regular plain mexican food. And the service is usually the worst part of the experience, as the servers don't really seem to care too much about anything. But again, it's nothing really extraordinary.

This last time was a little different. We asked if they could cook the huevos (eggs) scrambled for a huevos rancheros. The server said that they came fried. Blank face, just deal with it attitude. We said it's for the 4 year old, and we wanted it just as scrambled eggs on the side and that my mom and he would split the rest of the order and eat it.

I ordered an appetizer of nacho's. And when the server asked me what kind of meat, I kindly said I just want the appetizer. She repeated what kind of meat I wanted; which confused me, I didn't want meat on it. So I said chicken, what ever. I wasn't really hungry and just wanted to snack on some chips and cheese.

When asked what kinds of side we wanted, soup or fruit. My dad got soup, my mom and partner got fruit.

We got our drinks and the server said they were out of fruit. And that they could have soup instead. Which they did not want soup... server gave no indication that they understood.

Honestly at this point we were a little irritated as a group.

We got our food, and the nacho's I ordered somehow turned into super nacho's. Piled with stuff; beans, guac, sour cream, probably a 1/2 lb of sliced chicken, olives, green things... it was probably twice the size of anyone else's meal. I was in shock, normally I'd be happy. But 1, I wasn't hungry for this, 2 this isn't what I expected or really wanted.

My mom and son got their huevos rancheros, covered in hot sauce. So we asked for just eggs on the side, no sauce. The server was confused and would say she'd ask the cook. We just wanted 1 scrambled egg no sauce.

The server didn't wait to ask if anything else was wrong. We waited, the rest of family ate while I kinda stared at my meal, and my son got confused and refused to eat the spiced eggs.

The server came back, with what looked like 3+ scrambled eggs on a plate and walked away. I tried to get their attention throughout, to verify that I didn't get the wrong order.

So I sat, sipped my drink for a few minutes. Didn't touch my food.

The server eventually came back over and asked if they could fill our drinks again. So I asked them why I got such a huge order, and the server said that they only have one kind of nacho's. Still ignoring that I didn't really want all this food.

Let me state that normally, I would LOVE to have a big pile of suped up nacho's. I have nothing against getting what would normally be good food. But nacho's do not hold up well to refrigeration, and I didn't order a two person meal of nacho's. I was internally, really upset at the entire experience so far.

The coffee was good. The rest of the food was good. The service was some of the worst. I would have ranked this restaurant lower, but they have a good track record overall. We will be going to probably any other sit down mexican food joint rather than come back there any time soon. Probably Los Gallos (the place at the mall), or downtown at Raliberto's, or Pachanga's.</Text><pics>None<//pics>< Resp>
None</Resp>

< review>
We are definitely coming back here.  We went for dinner a couple of nights ago.  There were two servers, who were moving very quickly.  We got seated promptly, and menus brought over; nice extensive menu.  Entres were good.  My husband got a carnitas tostada house specialty heaped on his plate.  There was nothing left of it when he was done.  Not just good, but excellent.  Even the rice and beans were good.  Do order the guacamole.  It has the tang of lime juice, bringing back some of the best guacamole we had in Mexico.  I really like the pico de gallo.  While it was very hot, I just didn't care because the taste was so good.  Next time, though, I will also get a side of sour cream.  The servers and kitchen were quick, orders accurate.  If only they had agua fresca besides horchata!< /review>

<Rating>5<//Rating>< text>
We are repeat buyers from this retailer.  OK mattress stores are ALWAYS having a sale, but the prices here are as good as I can find anywhere.

Here's the deal... I am a big fella.  Just under 300 lbs.  I needed help finding a good long-range solution.

Bob, the manager, was very patient and knowledgeable regarding products offered.  He is also articulate and easy going.  Low pressure.  We had a 10 year old Beautyrest Black bed which we liked very much, but it was worn out.  Bob showed me several alternatives, some of which did not work well with my build and arthritis issues.

Did I mention Bob was very patient and low pressure?

And yes, after sampling at least 7 or 8 alternatives, I decided to repeat-buy another Beautyrest Black Calista (Firm) bed.  I knew this was a low risk purchase.

Looking later, on Google, I saw that our price was the EXACT SAME as with all other sources for this product, including on-line drop-shippers.

I will return to see Bob in another 10 years, God willing and "The creek don't rise."<//text>

I love this place! It is empty and so clean. All the staff are polite and happy. I almost don't want to write a review for fear more people will see this and come here! 1582259686603< /Time>
<user_name>Caden C< /user_name>< user>
118325113842322019712<//user>
< Review>
Okay ... who doesn't really like Costco? They practice a business model that many other big-box retailers strive for. Costco has a strong customer base and many loyal customers overall.

The savings at Costco is in bulk buying. Their buyers are also very strategic in product selection and provide a very good breadth of products. Selection is limited, but the products are well-considered.

Costco's return policy is actually very good. They are one of the few retailers that have customer satisfaction at the top of their priority list. Computers and electronics have a 90-day return policy which is best in the industry.

Their food court is also a wonderful perk for all customers including non-members. They lose money on most everything the food court sells and their management only sees this as a customer benefit that they don't want to change.

The membership fees are well worth it if you shop at Costco just more than a couple of times a month. Of course, you still need to be diligent on what you are buying, but overall the savings you can find for your everyday grocery here are easy to calculate.

This location is quite busy most of the time. It services most of the east valley here. There is also Costco Gas, which convenience adds to the patrons. Major holidays may propose some challenges though. (Thanksgiving, Christmas, 4th of July)

Key savings items and perks: Rotisserie chicken, toilet tissue, meats, bread, alcohol, luncheon meats, books, protein bars, and free food samples.< /Review>

5</Rate>

< Review>
AMAZING place.  If you have a Costco membership, and have not been here yet, by all means go.  They are a bit more food-centric (geared more towards convenience stores, restaurants, and caterers) and there are a lot of products available here that are not in the regular warehouses (stuff that they don't sell elsewhere, plus larger sizes/different packaging, flavors, etc) , plus they have professional cooking equipment and supplies and great cleaning and some office supplies. This is. Costco Business Center. Open to all Costco membership but with a somewhat different inventory.
It does NOT have:
A pharmacy
Gas station
Clothes
Butcher counter with prepared food
Rotisserie chicken, ribs etc
It DOES have:
Food service equipment & supplies
Small business office supplies
Janitorial supplies
Lots of food packaging
Typical & larger packages of produce
Large cuts of vacuum packed meats
A huge selection of sodas & juices.
Typical and larger canned items
Larger variety of baking supplies AND
Larger packages of baking supplies

< Review>
This is a Business Center version of Costco, The differences between the Business Center version and the others are: the Business Centers have more choices of the items that Costco's business customers need. For example they have a whole aisle of  energy drinks like Monster and Red Bull. They also stock some models of commercial grade restaurant equipment. Another example of differces is that Business Centers don't stock any clothing items.

This location has a huge indoor area for their food court, its located outside of the entrance gate. This is great because we can always benefit from filling up with a slice of pizza and a cup of lemonade before lifting all those massive items in bulk.</Review>
